    content: `
      <h2 id="why">Why YouTube Shorts Is the Fastest Growing Platform for Creators in 2026</h2>
      <p>YouTube Shorts crossed 100 billion daily views in 2025. The platform is actively rewarding new channels with outsized distribution — something that hasn't happened on YouTube's main feed since 2012. If you've been thinking about starting a YouTube channel, 2026 is still early enough in the Shorts gold rush to build a real audience without competing against channels with years of head start.</p>
      <p>And here's the part most people don't realize: you don't need a camera, editing experience, or any on-screen presence to build a successful Shorts channel. With the AI workflow in this guide, you need a topic, a script, and about 30 minutes per Short.</p>

      <h2 id="overview">The AI Shorts Workflow — Overview</h2>
      <p>The four-step system: Script → Voiceover → Visuals → Assembly. Each step has a primary AI tool. Once you've run through this process three or four times, each Short takes under 30 minutes from concept to upload-ready file.</p>

      <h2 id="steps">Step-by-Step: Creating Your First AI-Powered Short</h2>

      <h3>Step 1 — Script Your Short (5 minutes)</h3>
      <p>Use Jasper or Copy.ai to generate a 150–200 word script for your Short. Paste your hook idea and the main point you want to make. Edit the script to match your niche tone — the AI gives you a strong first draft, you give it personality and accuracy.</p>

      <h3>Step 2 — Generate Your Voiceover with ElevenLabs (5 minutes)</h3>
      <p>Paste your script into ElevenLabs. Select a voice that matches your channel personality — professional, casual, energetic, authoritative. Generate the audio, preview it, adjust the speed if needed, and download. ElevenLabs produces audio that sounds indistinguishable from a professional voice actor at a fraction of the cost.</p>

      <h3>Step 3 — Source or Generate Your Visuals (10 minutes)</h3>
      <p>For most Shorts, a combination of relevant stock footage and text overlays works better than AI-generated video, which can still look uncanny. Use Pexels or Pixabay for free stock footage, or Runway ML if you need specific visuals that don't exist in stock libraries. Download 3–5 clips relevant to your topic.</p>

      <h3>Step 4 — Assemble in Canva or CapCut (10 minutes)</h3>
      <p>Import your voiceover and footage into Canva's video editor or CapCut (both free at the level you need for Shorts). Add text overlays that match your script timing. Apply a branded color scheme and font. Export at 1080×1920 (9:16 vertical format) and upload to YouTube.</p>
    `,
